'''Kamioone no Mikoto''' (神大根王, dates of birth and death unknown) was an early figure of the [[Kofun period]] and the first '''[[Motozu Kuni no Miyatsuko]]''' (本巣国造, also known as [[Minomae Kuni no Miyatsuko]] or Mino Kuni no Miyatsuko).
== Overview == In the ''[[Kojiki]]'', he is also referred to as '''Yatsuri no Irihiko no Mikoto''' (八瓜入日子王). In the ''[[Kōka Tennōki]]'' section, he is identified as the ancestor of the [[Motozu Kuni no Miyatsuko|Mino Province Motozu Kuni no Miyatsuko]] and the Nagahata-no-Be lineage. In the ''[[Keikō Tennōki]]'', the name '''Ōone no Ō''' (大根王) is listed as the ancestor of the [[Mino Kuni no Miyatsuko]]. Similarly, the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' contains parallel accounts, where the name '''Kamuhone''' (神骨) appears as the Mino Kuni no Miyatsuko in the ''Keikō Tennōki''. Additionally, the ''[[Sendai Kuji Hongi]]'' in the ''Kuni no Miyatsuko Hongi'' section states that '''Yatsuri no Mikoto''' was appointed as the [[Minomae Kuni no Miyatsuko]] during the reign of [[Kōka Tennō|Emperor Kōka]]. Based on these records, the Motozu Kuni no Miyatsuko and Minomae Kuni no Miyatsuko are considered the same position.<ref>「古代中世 第一章 大化前代の加茂地方 第三節 国造と県主」『美濃加茂市史 通史編』[[美濃加茂市]]、1980th year 、202頁。</ref><ref>「第六章 大化前代 第二節 国造と県主」『各務原市史 通史編 自然・原始・古代・中世』各務原市教育委員会、1986th year 、181-184頁。</ref><ref>{{Cite book|author=[[Toshio Hōga|宝賀寿男]]|title=古代氏族の研究⑱ 鴨氏・服部氏 少彦名神の後裔諸族|publisher=青垣出版|year=2021|pages=81–82}}</ref>. The name ''Kamioone'' has been interpreted as meaning "the great root of Kamo."<ref name="kamo">{{Cite book|author=宝賀寿男|title=古代氏族の研究⑱ 鴨氏・服部氏 少彦名神の後裔諸族|publisher=青垣出版|year=2021|pages=86–87}}</ref>
The {{ill|Sōkei Ōtsuka Kofun|ja|宗慶大塚古墳|12=draft}}, located in {{ill|Motozu, Gifu Prefecture|ja|本巣市|12=draft}}'s Sōkei district, is believed to be the burial site of Kamioone no Mikoto or his descendants. The tomb dates back to the early Kofun period (4th century) and has historically been referred to as ''Ōtsuka Kofun''.
He is enshrined at multiple shrines, including {{ill|Takasaka Shrine|ja|高坂神社|12=draft}} and {{ill|Iwano Nishi Shrine|ja|伊波乃西神社|1=Iwa-no-Nishi Shrine|12=draft}}, and appears in the founding traditions of several others. At {{ill|Kamo Shrine|ja|加毛神社|12=draft}}, Kamioone no Mikoto is said to be the son of {{ill|Kamo no Hikozaka no Ō|ja|鴨君彦坐王|12=draft}} and the progenitor of the Mino Kuni no Miyatsuko, with his descendants spreading throughout southwestern Mino. It is said that the settlers worshiped {{ill|Kamowake Ikazuchi no Mikoto|ja|賀茂別雷命|12=draft}}, the ancestral deity of the Kamo clan.<ref>[https://www.gifu-jinjacho.jp/syosai.php?shrno=64&shrname=%E2%98%85%E5%8A%A0%E6%AF%9B%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE%E2%98%85 加毛神社] (Kamo Shrine), official website of the Gifu Prefecture Shrine Office.</ref>
== Genealogy == His father is said to be {{ill|Hikozaka no Ō|ja|日子坐王|12=draft}}, a prince of [[Kōka Tennō]], and his mother is {{ill|Okitsu Nagamizu Yorihime|ja|息長水依比売|12=draft}}, the daughter of {{ill|Amenokage no Mikoto|ja|天御影命|12=draft}}. He is believed to have had siblings, including {{ill|Mizuho no Mawaka no Ō|ja|水穂真若王|12=draft}}, the ancestor of the [[Ankoku no Miyatsuko]], and {{ill|Mizuho no Iyo Yorihime|ja|水穂五百依比売|12=draft}}, as well as {{ill|Mii no Tsuhime|ja|御井津比売|12=draft}}. However, the chronology described in the ''Kuni no Miyatsuko Hongi'' conflicts with the genealogical records in the ''Kojiki.''
