He is enshrined at multiple shrines, including {{ill|Takasaka Shrine|ja|高坂神社|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Iwano Nishi Shrine|ja|伊波乃西神社|1=Iwa-no-Nishi Shrine|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, and appears in the founding traditions of several others. At {{ill|Kamo Shrine|ja|加毛神社|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, Kamioone no Mikoto is said to be the son of {{ill|Kamo no Hikozaka no Ō|ja|鴨君彦坐王|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and the progenitor of the Mino Kuni no Miyatsuko, with his descendants spreading throughout southwestern Mino. It is said that the settlers worshiped {{ill|Kamowake Ikazuchi no Mikoto|ja|賀茂別雷命|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, the ancestral deity of the Kamo clan.<ref>[https://www.gifu-jinjacho.jp/syosai.php?shrno=64&shrname=%E2%98%85%E5%8A%A0%E6%AF%9B%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE%E2%98%85 加毛神社] (Kamo Shrine), official website of the Gifu Prefecture Shrine Office.</ref>
== Genealogy == His father is said to be {{ill|Hikozaka no Ō|ja|日子坐王|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, a prince of [[Kōka Tennō]], and his mother is {{ill|Okitsu Nagamizu Yorihime|ja|息長水依比売|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, the daughter of {{ill|Amenokage no Mikoto|ja|天御影命|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. He is believed to have had siblings, including {{ill|Mizuho no Mawaka no Ō|ja|水穂真若王|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, the ancestor of the [[Ankoku no Miyatsuko]], and {{ill|Mizuho no Iyo Yorihime|ja|水穂五百依比売|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, as well as {{ill|Mii no Tsuhime|ja|御井津比売|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. However, the chronology described in the ''Kuni no Miyatsuko Hongi'' conflicts with the genealogical records in the ''Kojiki.''
